# Documentation Standards

## No Emojis Policy

-   **NEVER** use emojis in code, comments, documentation, or commit messages
-   Use plain text status indicators: "Complete", "Pending", "Warning"
-   Use markdown formatting for emphasis instead of decorative symbols

## Python Docstrings (@002_python_standards)

```python
def function_name(param1: Type1, param2: Type2) -> ReturnType:
    """
    Brief description of function.

    Longer description if needed, explaining the purpose,
    behavior, and any important details.

    Args:
        param1: Description of param1
        param2: Description of param2

    Returns:
        Description of return value

    Raises:
        ExceptionType: When this exception occurs

    Example:
        >>> function_name(value1, value2)
        expected_result
    """
```

## Comments

-   **Explain Why**: Comments should explain "why", not "what"
-   **Keep Updated**: Update comments when code changes
-   **No Dead Code**: Never commit commented-out code

## Markdown Documentation

-   **Headers**: Use clear section headers with proper hierarchy
-   **Code Examples**: Include syntax-highlighted code examples
-   **Line Length**: Reasonable length (80-100 characters)
-   **Tables**: Use tables for structured data
-   **Links**: Use relative links where possible

## Code Review Checklist (@005_git_workflow)

Before submitting PR:

-   [ ] All tests pass (`pytest`)
-   [ ] Linting passes (`ruff check src/`)
-   [ ] Formatting applied (`black src/`)
-   [ ] Type checking passes (`mypy src/`)
-   [ ] Documentation updated
-   [ ] No emojis in code or documentation
-   [ ] Commit messages follow convention
-   [ ] Code coverage maintained or improved

## Project Documentation Structure

-   **`.docs/`**: Shared Brain with requirements, architecture, and specifications
-   **Templates**: Use `.docs/TEMPLATES/` for consistent documentation
-   **References**: Include relevant `.docs/` links in documentation
